<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
This post comes about because I was lectured the other day about killing a kodiak in WC by another druid, and that I was roleplaying poorly.  <BR>The general consensus on here seems to say that druids are caring, nature preserving, nice guys.  Where does this come from?  <BR>Historically, the druids were animists.  There isn't a whole lot of good written record on them, though.  The Romans had a rather biased view of them and the Christians weren't terribly charitible either.  <BR>     The nature that the druids sought to preserve were the sacred groves and that protection extended to particularly valuable plants (mistletoe).  Historically, there is nothing out there that says they were vegetarians, and it would be natural to assume that they had meat in their diet.  This means killing animals.  They didn't just kill animals, though.  There are records (both historical and archaeological) that suggest human sacrifice was practiced by the cultures that also spawned druids and it is thought that the druids were major players here.  There are Roman accounts of the druids sanctioning regicide.  If the current king proved too old and unable to carry on his duties he was sacrificed to make room for the new one.  These weren't necessarily nice guys.  <BR>     They worshipped nature, yes, this is apparent.  Did this mean they didn't exploit it?  Nope.  Life during the times of the druids was 'nasty, brutish, and short' and I think it is highly probable that many of the real druids out there were the same way.  <BR>     Verant has provided the druid class with many spells that enable us to kill/control animal class mobs.  All of the control animal spells result in the animal turning on us forcing us to kill it even if our original intentions were non-violent (saving a newbie from an agroed bear for instance and casting panic animal).  The only place where druids are penalized for killing wildlife is in Surefall.  This is consistent with the sacred glade I mentioned earlier.  A small area that is protected because of its sanctity to the druid cult.  So, the game system certainly doesn't support druids as vegetarian conservationists.  If anything, the druid class is rewarded with abilities and spells that allow us to exploit nature.  The only armor we can wear is leather or cloth and I don't see many druids working hard for that cloth look.    <BR>     Ok.  So...historically there is no precedent for a druid not to kill a bear.  Gamewise (mechanically) there is no reason not to kill a bear.  The only reason we have for not killing bears is that we are amiable to them, but I still don't get bad faction for killing one.  So I have no idea where this 'don't kill bears or you are a bad druid' thing came from other than misconceptions about what druids truly were or misconceptions about what Verant intended the druid to be.  When it comes down to it we all play the characters the way we want to roleplay regardless of these factors so why lecture someone about playing their character how they see fit?  <BR>     Anyway, I tried to fit this whole thing in a /tell back to this meddling but well meaning druid-cum-roleplaying-police officer, but I couldn't even get the first paragraph in so I thought I'd post here where I know everyone would just love to read my thoughts.   <BR>              <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
