<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
getting off topic a bit here...<BR>I am not trying to burst your bubble Jayde, but where are you getting your information on druids?  Is it a historically reliable source?  Does it have any grounding in anthropological research?  If it does I'd be interested in seeing the source material.  The druids you are referring to are what the neo-druids would have us believe the historical druids were.  The essential flaw in their proposal is that there is no recorded druidic history or culture written by druids.  The druids are all gone.  Their culture was destroyed by the Romans and whatever was left was demonized by Christianity.    <BR>Historically - The druids were observed and written about by many of the leading scholars in Rome.  Julius Caesar said he was impressed by their efficiency in 'agros' (farming).  He was also impressed by the druid's intolerance for weakness.  If a king proved too weak to rule he was thrown down and killed.  If you won the lottery in Celtic Britain you didn't win a million bucks; you were stoned to death because the gods of nature didn't favor you.  This is where the term scapegoat comes from by the way.  Pity for the weak didn't come along until Christianity set its foot in Britain.      <BR>As for French druids being burned as witches I have no idea to whom you are referring.  The druids were Celtic and only Celtic.  Prior to Christianity the Franks had an animist type religion (read Tacitus) that bore more resemblence to the shamans you see in EQ than the druids.  <BR>I like the neo-druids of today and I believe their beliefs are more in tune environmentally speaking than other religions, but if you want to say this is an old religion with deep historical roots you are mistaken.  The druids left no written record and that is why we can only depend on the Romans, Christians, and anthropologists to tell us what they were like, and admittedly, the druids were so demonized by the incoming Christians that it is hard to believe much that was recorded.  What exists in the archaeological record shows an extremely well organized agrarian culture...this means lots of farms.  The druids were the patriarchs/priests who had free rein to move about this culture and, according to Caesar, had strong control over the people's will.  Anyway, there is a lot of misinformation being flung about regarding Wicca and Druidism these days with the increased interest in all things mystical and unknown.  I think the real story is much simpler than it's been made out to be, and whilst neo-druidism might have a place in our modern culture it certainly doesn't match anything recorded anthropologically or historically speaking.      <BR>ok...back to being on topic...<BR>KILLING BEARS -<BR>Once again, Verant has created a new type of druid and this new druid doesn't have much grounding in existing historical or fantastic models.  Like most of Everquest it is more of an amalgamation of current popular fantasy lore with a good deal of TSR's Dungeons and Dragons thrown in.  <BR>For it to be wrong to kill a bear in EQ it would have to be mentioned somewhere in the official literature of the game, the code, or culturally reinforced by giving you bad faction if you DID kill a bear.  If someone chides me for it I am not going to justify it by saying 'I am an evil druid' because I am not.  I just don't live by the same rules that that particular individual chooses to limit themselves by.  <P>disclaimer - I am not just arguing this point to be contrary...I am a historical archaeologist by trade and this stuff truly fascinates me.  I love discussing it so please don't take this as a put down if you disagree with it.  I am not trying to flame anyone...just expressing my opinion.
</FONT>
