<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
My family sir. My grandmother's ancestors have been followers of the druid faith for many centuries. She is very eld and her memory and grasp on her surroundings has slipped. She gave me her journals along with her great grandmothers 5 years ago. Most of the writing is written in a language I can not decipher. Modern French it is not, and much of the script is faded to the point its not decipherable. Whether their faith was stemmed from the celts or a backwater french cult I know not. She always stressed the importance of treating each animal as an equal and taught me how to communicate with pack animals on their level at a young age. Her affinity for anything that grows is amazing you should see her herbal gardens. The family name was changed when they reached the america's from Di'Junae to Jones. They lived in the french canadian provinces for near a century and my grandmother's family moved to missouri and she married a cherokee native in 1936. Her husband was not registered as a citizen due to a squabble between the government and the reservations at that time. There is no record of birth for either of them my grandmother being born somewhere on a trail in Canada in 1914. I have the only written testament to their experiances during that time and I treasure it. Someday I hope to find someone that can help me decipher the script in her Greatgrandmothers diaries. As far as historically accurate and reliable? How reliable can one persons journal be. Each ones faith comes from the heart and your interpretation will be differant than others. I try and follow my grandmothers wishes as well as I can but the true druidic faith whether it be celtic, french, or some obscure branch that has been lost in the vaults of time is lost to us. <BR>Burned as Witches... My many times removed mother was burned as a witch when they realized the animals that resided with her near her home would protect her at the cost of their own lives. The year.. 1648. Her name was Peronnette d'Arstigno. I only have this name and family history to confirm this. Unfortunately so much has been lost I can give you no more.<P>--------------------<P>Jayde <BR>Dammiana druid of 46 seasons of growth
