<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Thanks Jayde, <P>Once again, I didn't mean any offense and I find your family history fascinating.  I don't doubt the witch burning; my only doubts were the presence of druids in France during the period of witch burning which occurred long after the Celtic Druids were lost to history.  I also don't mean to insult your faith.  I strongly believe, as you do, that one's faith is in their heart.  This is not a matter for history books and archaeologists. Any faith that believes in living in tune with nature and the other living things around us gets high marks in my book.  I also agree with you that the original druidic culture left very little for us to study and that is unfortunate, and gives those who would like to be druids today very little to go on beyond the basic tenants of the faith.  I'd recommend getting those journals translated as soon as possible.  They might be faded badly now, but it will only get worse, and a linguist will be more help now than next year.  Their historical value could be quite significant, regardless.  As for your family's practice of druidism and their journal this isn't enough to convince me that there is any true connection between today's practitioners of neo-druidism (even if they were from the 15th century...it's still too late) and the Celtic druids.    <BR>     And, yes, Cirys...the Celts did manage to range pretty far, but did they make a significant enough impact on these far flung cultures to leave much of a mark?  Certainly not enough of a mark to leave a detailed record of their ethnohistory.  Historically, druidism was only practiced in the British Isles to my knowledge.  I'd very much enjoy hearing about any *verifiable* sources that say otherwise.<BR>     This is all moot however...my concern is the fact that several players have gotten it into their heads what druids can and can't do in the game when there is no official guideline on how to actually roleplay a druid.  There is no real historical record that matches what I am being told is a good druid.  Some players would have me believe the only good druid is a dead druid.  The closest druid that seems to match EQ's druid is the D&D druid...the races match up, the general ideaology matches up and nowhere does it say I can't kill bears   <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
