<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_profile&u=00010113" target=_blank>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/profile.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Profile for Uilian"></A>  &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=private_message&u=00010113"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/priv_message.gif" BORDER='0' ALT="Send New Private Message"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=11&t=000721&reply_num=000016&u=00010113"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=11&t=000721&replyto=000016"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Yup, Curumir is right.  I did some research and found the Celtic culture was spread out a lot more than I had originally thought (it sucks to be wrong).  The time period where I spend most of my studies starts with the decline of Rome, and by then the Celts were limited to the British Isles. <BR>     But - from the period of 800 b.c. to 200 b.c. the Celts were spread from Turkey to Britain.  There is mention of a 'Keltoi' people in Hesiod's anabasis from 6th century b.c. Greece.  There is the anecdote that Curumir mentions where Caesar encountered Celts in Gaul (the term Gaelic comes comes from the word Gaul in fact).  Two of the most noted Celtic archaeological sites aren't in Britain at all.  One is in Austria (Halstatt) and another further west called La T'ene.  It is believed that all of these Celtic tribes had the druid sub-culture as an integral part of their communities.  Among many of the observations I read, though, it was frequently pointed out that the druids were very secretive and committed their practices only to memory and not to written record.  When the druids did write it was in Greek according to a few early sources.  I was surprised to see the Celts labled as sun worshipers according to more than one anthropological/archaeological account.  Also, as Curimir points out, there is no surviving written record dating back to Celtic society regardless of their location beyond what was written about them by contemporaries.  It is noted that they did possess written language skills (druids writing in Greek for non-theological matters).  <BR>     As far as the Picts go, there were two tribes...a northern and a southern.  The southern Picts were in Gaul as well (not northern France or Normandy...this was the domain of the Franks, a Germanic people), and the northern and more well known tribe resided in the northern part of Britain where Scotland is today.  The picts promptly disappeared in the middle of the 11th century a.d. and it is one of history's mysteries as to where they went.  <BR>     Stonehenge - I still strongly believe that the Celts existed far too late to have built this.  It is most commonly believed that Stonehenge was built by a bronze age culture called the Beaker People (because of the ceramic beakers found in their grave sites) or someone from the same period of time.  There seems to be a lot of evidence that the druids did use stonehenge due to the presence of ritually sacrificed remains discovered there.  Pretty interesting stuff really. But why spend all this time here saying this?  What possible relevence does it have to the topic at hand?  Not much.<BR>     My whole purpose in originally posting was to bring some awareness that the druids are not the warm and cuddly lovers of life and nature that a lot of people are claiming.  We have allowed our own 21st century concerns with destruction of the environment, animal rights issues, and fascination with mysticism to define them in our own image.  This new image is what are being called the neo-druids, and while I recognize their issues as being valid ones I find it very hard to swallow that they bear much resemblence to the Celtic druids of yore.  I believe if we knew the whole story of who the druids were (historically) we'd find them rather repugnant.  <BR>     I saw a recomendation for Mists of Avalon, and I would like to counter with Bernard Cornwell's The Winter King.  Probably the best telling of the Arthurian legend I have read in a long time.  Mists of Avalon was pretty good, but Winter King is a lot grittier and more realistic when compared to what we know historically.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
